76561197979513985,Recommended,331920,21875043,"Posted: 16 March, 2016",all,Kyson,"When I was younger I played the hell out of this game on my old Dell Latidude with windows XP, the game ran smoothly with no problems, it was very forgiving on outdated systems back thenFirst impressions:You will no doubt be charmed by the groovy soundtrack this game has to offer, I like each and every song and I can appreciate a good soundtrack to play to, the ambience in the airport is also so immersive, hearing the flight announcements, chattering and bustling of people going on holiday and returning from holiday, and the game is rather easy to start playing thanks to the advisor that acts as a tutorial whenever you do something new for the first timeGameplay:It's simple, you control your airline CEO (I like Phoenix/Falcon Lines because of where their offices are placed) - and you go your day to day business of taking flights and ordering your planes to carry out orders, you need to make sure your security is in check (security office is on the top floor on the airport, look for a window that looks out of place). You need to buy a filofax and a cellphone so you dont have to keep going back to your office, once you unlock your laptop you can carry out orders from anywhere and make some changes to your planes. You can even hire a saboteur to make life hard for your opponents, from placing heavily salted food on board, to giving them a computer virus, or even planting a bomb in their office or causing a plane crash! Of course the airport manager will eventually find out it's you and a hefty fine will come your way.Like any good CEO, you need to keep the cash coming in and the expenses low, for this you have to hire and fire staff, your friendly personnel team will help you out with this, and you can hire advisors to give you a little edge over the competition. You can buy and sell shares of the other 3 airlines, as well as buy and sell planes. You have so much to work with and at first it can be a struggle to juggle it all, but as I said, your lovely advisor will chip in whenever you feel clueless, she is a button click away.Sound:As said above, the soundtrack is very charming and upbeat, definitely a good choice to have this kind of music. The ambience is top notch and makes you feel like you are in the airport. Unfortunately you can't seem to change the music but why would you want to, and the music settings are a little hard to balance because some sound effects are rather loud to begin with, so spend some time balancing ambience, music and sound effectsVisuals:It's a 2003 game so don't expect anything fancy, but the cartoon style graphics and smooth frame rate make this game very very enjoyable to play, the game will only lag if you use the cheat to bring a massive crowd to the airport (i think this is just cosmetic).Multiplayer:Unfortunately I never managed to play this game on multiplayer so I can't comment on this, but I'm sure your imagination will tell you it's rather fun, the AI in the game is so predictable that I can remember exactly who drops first, second and third to leave me as the sole CEO, because of what they do (issuing more shares, overzealous sabotage leading to excessive fines from the airport managerOverall:I give this game a 9, it's hard to flaw given that it was a very very good game at the time, I seem to remember that in the early 2000s to 2005 there was an influx of rather good tycoon and simulation games, for example Monopoly Tycoon, Mall Tycoon, Rollercoaster Tycoon (who can forget that), Hotel Giant and The Sims, I'll have no problems in admitting Airline Tycoon should also be on that list.Get this game, it's £7 and you'll have lots of fun with it, just make sure to get your security up to scratch first!"
