,Not Recommended,331920,21821516,"Posted: 13 March, 2016",all,TheyCalledMeMad,"The first few hours are a game of short-term memory. You go to the travel agency, and it lists six or so trips you can assign to your planes. Now you have to remember which plane is going to be in which city at which time - if you pick up a ticket that you can't fly, you pay a fairly-hefty penalty. If you don't pick up enough tickets, you won't be able to beat your competitors.Now you've picked up your tickets, it's time to assign them to your planes! The new short-term memory game is to remember which airports have which abbreviations in their schedules (London is LHR, for instance) - the airline-schedule side of the screen uses the airport-abbreviation codes, and the ticket side of the screen uses the city name. Then assign the tickets to the planes in the most efficient way so you aren't flying the planes empty too often - using a bit of trial an error, since you haven't memorized the airport abbreviations yet.And the short-term memory game is made harder because your guy has to actually WALK between the travel agencies and your office. Repeatedly. Picking up no more than six tickets at a time. (And really, no more than three tickets, because the profitability of about half of the tickets is abysmal.) While you try to remember which plane has a capacity of 180 passengers, and which plane has a capacity of 90 passengers, and which city it's in so it can get to the ticket's starting city in time, and when it's available, and dangit, this much memorization just isn't fun. I found myself wondering whether the game should do this scheduling automatically, only to realize that this short-term memory thing is supposed to *be* the game.Also, don't work for Honey Airlines. Their office is the one furthest away from the travel agencies, so your guy spends even longer walking."
